04069nam a22005055i 9780226731148DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082005ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267311487 a10.7208/97802267311482doi  a(DE-B1597)523597  a(OCoLC)747946400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ127.E8bR83 2005eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a551.7094/090332221 aRudwick, Martin J. S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBursting the Limits of Time :bThe Reconstruction of Geohistory in the Age of Revolution /cMartin J. S. Rudwick. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (732 p.) :b145 halftones, 34 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA note on footnotes -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. UNDERSTANDING THE EARTH -- tPart Two. RECONSTRUCTING GEOHISTORY -- tCoda: Retrospect and Prospect -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1650, Archbishop James Ussher of Armagh joined the long-running theological debate on the age of the earth by famously announcing that creation had occurred on October 23, 4004 B.C. Although widely challenged during the Enlightenment, this belief in a six-thousand-year-old planet was only laid to rest during a revolution of discovery in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. In this relatively brief period, geologists reconstructed the immensely long history of the earth-and the relatively recent arrival of human life. Highlighting a discovery that radically altered existing perceptions of a human's place in the universe as much as the theories of Copernicus, Darwin, and Freud did, Bursting the Limits of Time is a herculean effort by one of the world's foremost experts on the history of geology and paleontology to sketch this historicization of the natural world in the age of revolution. Addressing this intellectual revolution for the first time, Rudwick examines the ideas and practices of earth scientists throughout the Western world to show how the story of what we now call "deep time" was pieced together. He explores who was responsible for the discovery of the earth's history, refutes the concept of a rift between science and religion in dating the earth, and details how the study of the history of the earth helped define a new branch of science called geology. Rooting his analysis in a detailed study of primary sources, Rudwick emphasizes the lasting importance of field- and museum-based research of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. Bursting the Limits of Time, the culmination of more than three decades of research, is the first detailed account of this monumental phase in the history of science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGeologyzEuropexHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezEuropexHistoryy18th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226731148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226731148.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles